[s1; Bazaar user guide&]
[s0; [2 Do you want to use certain package from Bazaar, and you don`'t 
know how? Don`'t worry, using Bazaar is very easy.]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0;2%- &]
[ {{10000f0;g0;^t/25b4/25 [s0;# [*+117 1. Package Download]]}}&]
[s0;2%- &]
[s0; [2 By default the Bazaar packages are already installed together 
with U`+`+.]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0; [2 If you don`'t find a `"Bazaar`" folder inside your `"upp`" 
main folder, you have to download it. There are two ways:]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0;i150;O0; [2 The easy way]&]
[s0;l160;i150;O0; [2 Download the latest release in .tar.gz format 
from ][^http`:`/`/code`.google`.com`/p`/upp`-mirror`/downloads`/list^2 here][2 .]&]
[s0;l160;i150;O0; [2 Unzip the file in upp folder and that is all.]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0;i150;O0; [2 The less easy way]&]
[s0;l160;i150;O0; [2 Install a ][^http`:`/`/subversion`.tigris`.org`/^2 Subversion][2  
client like TortoiseSVN, SmartSVN, SlikSVN or just a `"apt`-get 
install subversion`" in Linux. Be sure that in Windows the svn 
client is in PATH environment variable although this is usually 
done by installer.]&]
[s0;l160;i150;O0; [2 Download to your Upp folder from here ]&]
[s0;l160;2 &]
[s0;l480; [C$7;2 http://upp`-mirror.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0;l288; [2 or run this command in a command window: ]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0;l480; [C$7;2 svn checkout http://upp`-mirror.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/ 
my`-upp]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0;2 &]
[ {{10000f0;g0;^t/25b4/25 [s0;# [*+117 2. Setting up Assembly]]}}&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0; [2 Choose or create an Assembly where will your new package reside 
(MyApps is a common choice). Add bazaar path to `"Package nests`" 
of desired Assembly (see ][^topic`:`/`/ide`/app`/ConfiguringPackagesAssemblies`$en`-us^2 C
onfiguring Packages `& Assemblies][2 ).]&]
[s0;2 &]
[s0; [2 Now choose/create new package in the modified Assembly, and 
use `"Add package`" on it to add some of bazaar`'s packages. 
Don`'t forget also to use particular #includes at proper places 
of source code.]&]
[s0;2 &]
